\section solvers2a Computing a Bound on the Best Sensor Placement Value

The following example shows how the lower bound can be computed on the best possible sensor
placement with a similar syntax:

\verbatim
../../bin/sp --path=../../bin --path=../../etc/mod --network=Net3 --objective=ec
	--ub=ns,5 --solver=pico --compute-bound

read_impact_files:  /home/wehart/src/spot-limited/examples/simple/Net3_ec.impact

Number of Nodes                :  97
Number of Contamination Impacts: 9458

Running PICO...
../../bin/PICO --debug=1 --lpType=clp   --onlyRootLP=true Net3.mod
	/home/wehart/src/spot-limited/examples/simple/Net3.dat
... PICO done
Computing a lower bound
Objective lower bound: 8478.96737288
Done with sp
\endverbatim


\section solvers2b Minimizing the Number of Sensors

We can "invert" the sensor placement problem by minimizing the number
of sensors subject to a constraint on the extent of contamination.
Note that the following example finds a solution with a single sensor
that meets our goal of 40000 mean extent of contamination.

\verbatim
../../bin/sp --path=../../bin --path=../../etc/mod --network=Net3 --objective=ns
	--ub=ec,40000 --solver=pico

