\section solvers5 Limited-Memory Sensor Placement Techniques

Controlling memory usage is a critical issue for solving large sensor
placement formulations.  This is a particular challenge for IP methods,
both both the GRASP and Lagrangian heuritics can have difficultly solving
very large problems on standard workstations.  A variety of mechanisms
have been integrated into \c sp to reduce the problem representation
size while preserving the structure of the sensor placement problem.

The \ref scenarioAggrExecutable "scenarioAggr" method described in
the previous section is one possible strategy.  This tool compresses
the impact file while preserving the fundamental structure of the
impact file, and this tool is appropriate when optimizing for mean
performance objectives.  Similarly, the \ref filter_impactsExecutable
"filter_impacts" script can limit the sensor placement to only consider
contamination incidents that are "sufficiently bad" in the worst-case.
Another strategy is to limit the number of sensor placements, using
the \c --sensor-locations option described above; eliminating feasible
locations reduces the problem representation used by the \c sp solvers.

Two other strategies are also supported by \c sp.  First, the GRASP
heuristic has several options for controlling how memory is mmanaged.
The \c --heurisitic-representation option can be used to control how the
neighborhood move operator is performed.  By default, a dense matrix is
precomputed to perform neighborhood moves quickly, but a sparse matrix
can be used to perform neighborhood moves with less memory.  It should be
noted that the Lagrangian heuristic requires less memory than the GRASP
heuristic, and thus similar techniques have not been developed for it.

Second, the <i>witness aggregation</i> technique can be used to limit
the size of the sensor placement formulation.  This term refers to the
variables in the IP formulation that "witness" a contamination event.
By default, variables that witness contamination events with the same
impact are aggregated, and this typically reduces the IP constraint
matrix by a significant amount.  Further reductions can be performed
with more aggressive aggregations.

To illustrate the use of witness aggregation, we generated impact
files with the \c spot/etc/tsg/hourly.tsg TSG file.  The following
table illustrates the use of the two witness aggregation options when
optimizing the mean extent of contamination: \c --aggregation-percent
and \c --aggregation-ratio (used with the \c --distinguish-detection
option, which helps this aggregation option).  The second line of data
in this table is the default aggregation, which has about half as many
non-zero values in the IP constraint matrix.  Both the percent and ratio
aggregation strategies effectively reduce the problem size while finding
near-optimal solutions.

<center>
<table>
<tr>
<td bgcolor="lightgray">Type</td><td bgcolor="lightgray">Aggr Value</td><td bgcolor="lightgray">Binary Vars</td><td bgcolor="lightgray">IP Nonzeros</td><td bgcolor="lightgray">Solution Value</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>None</td><td>NA</td><td>97</td><td align="right">220736</td><td align="right">8525</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Percent</td><td>0.0</td><td>97</td><td align="right">119607</td><td align="right">8525</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Percent</td><td>0.125</td><td>97</td><td align="right">49576</td><td align="right">9513</td>
</tr>

<tr>
